# CODEOWNERS — risk-weighted review enforcement
#
# Last entry wins. The default rule sits at the top so paths
# below it that match a narrower glob override. Required-review
# enforcement happens at branch protection level (GitHub's
# "Require review from Code Owners" toggle); this file just names
# WHO the reviewers are per area. Branches protected via this
# rule:
#   - main (release-cutting, all production-bound code)
#
# Anchors the trunk-based-release.md "Separation of duties"
# section in the repo state — without CODEOWNERS, the prose is
# advisory; with it, "PR author can't merge their own
# release-impacting change" becomes a GitHub-level constraint.

# Default — every file routes to the maintainer until split.
*                                       @klinux

# --- CI + supply-chain surface (highest blast radius) ---------
# A bad workflow can publish unsigned images, leak the
# GITHUB_TOKEN, or skip the CI-green gate. Treat as the
# separation-of-duties hottest layer: author CANNOT self-approve
# (branch-protection ruleset "exclude_pr_author" is the actual
# enforcer; this file makes ownership explicit so reviewers know
# they own the policy implications, not just the YAML diff).
/.github/workflows/                     @klinux
/.github/CODEOWNERS                     @klinux

# --- Database migrations (forward-only contract) --------------
# Migrations are forward-only and backward-compatible by policy.
# A reviewer needs to confirm the expand/contract shape AND the
# column-nullability semantics, not just the SQL syntax. Naming
# the owner here surfaces that responsibility on every PR diff.
/server/migrations/                     @klinux

# --- Helm chart + Kubernetes manifests ------------------------
# Chart changes ride v0.x.y to operators directly; a regression
# in default values (resource limits, RBAC bindings, NetworkPolicy
# scope) lands in every fresh install. Same review attention as
# CI: production-impacting, hard to roll back via "just bump
# again" because operators may pin.
/charts/                                @klinux

# --- Proto / gRPC contracts -----------------------------------
# A breaking proto change cascades to every generated binding
# (Go server, Go agent, TS web). buf-breaking guards the wire
# shape; the owner here is responsible for the COMPATIBILITY
# semantics (deprecate vs delete, version bump, etc.) that buf
# can't see.
/proto/                                 @klinux

# --- Auth, secrets, RBAC --------------------------------------
# Substitution code, secret resolution, and RBAC checks form
# the security boundary. The CLAUDE.md "Security is not optional"
# section governs these paths; a reviewer needs to track
# constant-time compare + single-pass substitution + LogMasks
# coverage on EVERY change here, not just the smoking-gun ones.
/server/internal/secrets/               @klinux
/server/internal/auth/                  @klinux
/server/internal/api/authapi/           @klinux
/server/internal/api/admin/             @klinux

# --- Webhook signature verification ---------------------------
# HMAC/token compare paths for GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket. A
# signature-skip regression here is a public exploit.
/server/internal/webhook/               @klinux
